  eprinttype = {arxiv},
  primaryclass = {astro-ph},
  abstract = {We select galaxies from the IllustrisTNG hydrodynamical simulations (\$M\_*{$>$}10\^9\textasciitilde\textbackslash rm M\_\textbackslash odot\$ at \$0\textbackslash le z\textbackslash le2\$) and characterize the shapes and evolutions of their UVJ and star-formation rate -- stellar mass (SFR-\$M\_*\$) diagrams. We quantify the systematic uncertainties related to different criteria to classify star-forming vs. quiescent galaxies, different SFR estimates, and by accounting for the star formation measured within different physical apertures. The TNG model returns the observed features of the UVJ diagram at \$z\textbackslash leq2\$, with a clear separation between two classes of galaxies. It also returns a tight star-forming main sequence (MS) for \$M\_*{$<$}10\^\{10.5\}\textbackslash,\textbackslash rm M\_\textbackslash odot\$ with a \$\textbackslash sim0.3\$ dex scatter at \$z\textbackslash sim0\$ in our fiducial choices. If a UVJ-based cut is adopted, the TNG MS exhibits a downwardly bending at stellar masses of about \$10\^\{10.5-10.7\}\textasciitilde\textbackslash rm M\_\textbackslash odot\$. Moreover, the model predicts that \$\textbackslash sim80\textbackslash,(50)\$ per cent of \$10\^\{10.5-11\}\textasciitilde\textbackslash rm M\_\textbackslash odot\$ galaxies at \$z=0\textasciitilde (z=2)\$ are quiescent and the numbers of quenched galaxies at intermediate redshifts and high masses are in better agreement with observational estimates than previous models. However, shorter SFR-averaging timescales imply higher normalizations and scatter of the MS, while smaller apertures lead to underestimating the galaxy SFRs: overall we estimate the inspected systematic uncertainties to sum up to about \$0.2-0.3\$ dex in the locus of the MS and to about 15 percentage points in the quenched fractions. While TNG color distributions are clearly bimodal, this is not the case for the SFR logarithmic distributions in bins of stellar mass (SFR\$\textbackslash geq 10\^\{-3\}\textasciitilde\textbackslash rm M\_\textbackslash odot\$yr\$\^\{-1\}\$). Finally, the slope and \$z=0\$ normalization of the TNG MS are consistent with observational findings; however, the locus of the TNG MS remains lower by about \$0.2-0.5\$ dex at \$0.75\textbackslash le z{$<$}2\$ than the available observational estimates taken at face value.},
